<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=98385256866708></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f98385256866708><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98385256866708>RE: Shaman Pets</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=98385256866708#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Mar 5th 11:22 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ahhh.&nbsp;&nbsp;I disagree on your "when NOT to summon a wolf pal...."<br><br>This all assumes you know how to control your pet *wink*<br><br>1)In dungeons.  The only time you shouldn't summon one in a dungeon is if your group is clearing it, aka moving from one end to the other.  However, if you are camping a room, as most people do, go ahead.  Granted, you still have to be careful to control your pet, but in general you have to anyway.  Just use the /pet guard here after you summon him when you get where you are going.<br><br>2)When you are the only healer. This is a &gt;perfect&lt; time to summon a pet before things get hairy.  Because you will be on your butt medding 90% of the time, your pet allows you to contribute to the group damage.  He also can act as an emergency buffer for when you aggro heal.  If you leave /pet taunt on, he will be higher on the list than you most of the time, but not higher than the tank (pet taunt doesn't work real well for people other than the owner, ask a magician).  As long as you have the mana to spare, summon him.<br><br>3) Tank heavy or lots of pets.  Summon him anyway!  Most tanks do not complain about your little wolfie buddy nipping at the heals of a mob.  Over the course of several fights, he will do several thousands of points of damage, cutting the overall fighting time down, along with less healing/nuking/recovery time needed.  If there are already 4 other pets (read magician and necro) just have him /pet guard here.  You can always sacrifice him on an overpull.<br><br>Basically, the only time NOT to summon a pet really is when there are lots of multipulls, you have an enchanter mezzing, and you, er um, suck at controlling your doggy.  The only other consideration happens to be if the room/dungeon you are in has horrible pathing.<br><br>Trust me.  That little nipper has a lot of damage potential in him.  Just make sure you know how to control the little scamp.<br><br>Gorthin Spiritcaller<br>51 Shaman BB<br>Drindal <br>43 Monk BB<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
